## LakebaseAuth: mint JWTs via Postgres API for Autoscaling-only projects (fixes "Database instance 'ontobricks-test' not found")

Context: after the previous "Postgres-API fallback for Autoscaling
endpoint lookup" change, the dev sandbox switched bindings from the
Autoscaling project ``ontobricks-app`` (also visible on the legacy
Database Instance API) to ``ontobricks-test`` (created via the
Autoscaling UI / Postgres API only). Project resolution worked —
``LakebaseAuth.instance_name`` correctly returned ``ontobricks-test``
via the Postgres API endpoint walk — but the JWT-minting path then
called ``WorkspaceClient.database.generate_database_credential(
instance_names=['ontobricks-test'])``, which 404s on Autoscaling-only
projects. Symptom on the Registry page:
``Could not query Lakebase: Lakebase connection failed: Failed to
mint Lakebase JWT for instance 'ontobricks-test': Database instance
'ontobricks-test' not found.``

Root cause: the Lakebase Autoscaling stack uses the Postgres API
(``POST /api/2.0/postgres/credentials``) to mint endpoint-scoped JWTs.
Projects created via the Autoscaling UI or Postgres API are invisible
to the legacy ``database.list_database_instances`` / ``database.
generate_database_credential`` pair; only projects also created via
the Database Instance API or the Lakehouse/Provisioned UI are visible
on both. ``LakebaseAuth.password`` only knew about the legacy mint.

Fix: add a Postgres-API mint path and pick between the two based on
how the project was discovered.

- ``self._endpoint_resource`` caches the full endpoint resource path
  (``projects/<project_id>/branches/<branch_id>/endpoints/<endpoint_id>``)
  whenever ``_lookup_via_postgres_api`` matches PGHOST against
  ``status.hosts.host`` / ``read_only_host``.
- ``password()`` now picks:
  1. ``POST /api/2.0/postgres/credentials`` with the cached endpoint
     resource when ``_endpoint_resource`` is populated (Autoscaling-
     only projects).
  2. The legacy ``database.generate_database_credential(
     instance_names=[<name>])`` when the project was resolved via the
     legacy API or via an explicit ``DATABASE_INSTANCE_NAME``
     override (covers Provisioned + dual-visibility Autoscaling).
- Belt-and-braces fallback: if the legacy mint raises with the
  ``Database instance '<name>' not found`` wire signature, we walk
  the Postgres API once to populate ``_endpoint_resource`` and retry
  the mint there. Catches the case where ``DATABASE_INSTANCE_NAME``
  was set explicitly to an Autoscaling-only project name. Other
  legacy errors (5xx, network) still bubble up as
  ``ValidationError`` so we don't mask transient outages with a
  silent retry.

Changes:

- ``src/back/core/databricks/LakebaseAuth.py``
  - New module-level helper ``_looks_like_instance_not_found`` —
    string-match against the legacy wire error to gate the fallback.
  - ``__init__`` initialises the new ``_endpoint_resource`` field.
  - ``_lookup_via_postgres_api`` now also stashes the matched
    endpoint's full resource path on ``self._endpoint_resource``.
  - ``password()`` refactored: forces ``instance_name`` resolution
    first (so the endpoint resource is populated when applicable),
    then dispatches to either ``_mint_via_postgres_api`` or
    ``_mint_via_database_instances``. Logs which path minted.
  - Two new private helpers:
    ``_mint_via_database_instances(name)`` (legacy SDK call,
    factored out) and ``_mint_via_postgres_api(endpoint_resource)``
    (``POST /api/2.0/postgres/credentials`` with body
    ``{"endpoint": <endpoint_resource>}``).

- ``tests/test_lakebase_auth.py``
  - New ``TestPasswordMintingPath`` class covering:
    * Autoscaling-only project (resolved via Postgres API) mints via
      ``POST /api/2.0/postgres/credentials``; the legacy SDK call is
      asserted to *never* run, and the body shape (``{"endpoint":
      "projects/.../endpoints/primary"}``) is pinned so a regression
      on the request schema gets caught loudly. Also asserts the
      cached token short-circuits the second call.
    * Provisioned-style instance (resolved via legacy API) keeps the
      legacy mint with ``instance_names=[<name>]``; the Postgres API
      is asserted to *never* be called.
    * Explicit ``DATABASE_INSTANCE_NAME`` override pointing at an
      Autoscaling-only project: legacy mint 404s, fallback walks the
      Postgres API and retries the mint there.
    * Random non-not-found legacy errors (e.g. 500, network) bubble
      up as ``ValidationError`` and do *not* trigger a silent
      Postgres-API fallback.

Test plan:

- ``uv run pytest tests/test_lakebase_auth.py -q`` — 14 passed
  (4 new on top of the 10 from the previous Postgres-API-fallback
  change).
- ``uv run pytest -q`` — full suite green (1887 passed).
- Manual: redeploy the dev-lakebase target (``databricks bundle
  deploy -t dev-lakebase``) bound to project ``ontobricks-test``.
  Registry page no longer 500s on the JWT mint; ``+ Initialize``
  succeeds and creates the ``ontobricks_registry`` schema inside
  the bound database (``databricks_postgres`` for ``ontobricks-test``
  until a custom database is provisioned).

## LakebaseAuth: Postgres-API fallback for Autoscaling endpoint lookup (fixes "Failed to mint Lakebase JWT for instance '?'")

Context: on the deployed dev sandbox (``ontobricks-dev``) bound to the
Autoscaling project ``ontobricks-app``, the Registry page returned a
500 ``Could not query Lakebase: Lakebase connection failed: Failed to
mint Lakebase JWT for instance '?': No Lakebase instance matched
PGHOST='ep-damp-art-d1l8gclo.database.us-west-2.cloud.databricks.com'.
Set DATABASE_INSTANCE_NAME to the instance name.``

Root cause: ``LakebaseAuth.instance_name`` only consulted the legacy
**Database Instance API** (``w.database.list_database_instances``) and
matched ``PGHOST`` against ``read_write_dns`` / ``read_only_dns`` of
each instance. For Lakebase Autoscaling projects whose regional
endpoint hostname (``ep-<id>.database.<region>.cloud.databricks.com``)
is the *only* one Databricks Apps injects as ``PGHOST``, the legacy
DNS fields don't carry that value — so the lookup returned empty,
and the wrapper in ``password()`` re-raised it as ``Failed to mint
Lakebase JWT for instance '?'`` (the inner ``ValidationError`` is
caught before ``self._instance_name`` is ever populated, hence the
``'?'`` placeholder).

Fix: extend the resolution chain with a third step that falls through
to the **Postgres API** when the legacy lookup misses. Walks
``/api/2.0/postgres/projects`` → branches → endpoints and matches
``status.hosts.host`` / ``status.hosts.read_only_host`` against
``PGHOST``. The project_id (final segment of ``projects/<id>``) is
returned as the instance name — ``generate_database_credential``
accepts it directly via ``instance_names=[<project_id>]``, so no
change is needed in the JWT-minting path.

Resolution order is now:

1. ``DATABASE_INSTANCE_NAME`` env var (explicit override).
2. Database Instance API (legacy / Provisioned + DAB-created projects).
3. Postgres API endpoint walk (Autoscaling projects created via the
   Autoscaling UI / Postgres API).

Changes:

- ``src/back/core/databricks/LakebaseAuth.py``
  - Module + property docstrings updated to describe the new
    fallback step.
  - ``instance_name`` refactored into two helpers:
    ``_lookup_via_database_instances`` (existing logic, factored out)
    and ``_lookup_via_postgres_api`` (new). The latter uses
    ``WorkspaceClient.api_client.do`` directly so it works on every
    SDK version regardless of whether ``w.postgres`` is bound on the
    public surface. Hosts are compared lower-cased + stripped, same
    convention as the Database Instance API path.
  - Failure semantics preserved: any unhandled exception from
    *either* lookup is wrapped into ``ValidationError`` with the same
    "Could not resolve Lakebase instance name from PGHOST=… Set
    DATABASE_INSTANCE_NAME explicitly." guidance message. ``PGAPPNAME``
    is still never consulted.

- ``tests/test_lakebase_auth.py``
  - Existing ``test_pgappname_is_never_used_as_instance_name`` updated
    to also stub the Postgres-API ``api_client.do`` so the assertion
    survives the new fallback step.
  - New ``TestPostgresApiFallback`` class covering:
    * Falls back to Postgres API when the Database Instance API
      returns no match (the deployed-app regression case, with the
      exact ``ep-damp-art-d1l8gclo`` PGHOST).
    * Matches against ``read_only_host`` too.
    * Database Instance API hit short-circuits the Postgres API walk
      (verified by an ``AssertionError`` side-effect on
      ``api_client.do``).
    * No match anywhere → raises with the ``ep-…`` host echoed back.
    * Postgres API failure is wrapped into ``ValidationError``.

Test plan:

- ``uv run pytest tests/test_lakebase_auth.py -q`` — 10 passed
  (5 new).
- ``uv run pytest -q`` — full suite green (1883 passed).
- Manual recovery options for the running deployed app, in order of
  preference:
  1. Redeploy the dev-lakebase target (``databricks bundle deploy
     -t dev-lakebase``) — picks up the code fix automatically.
  2. As a hot-fix without a redeploy, set
     ``DATABASE_INSTANCE_NAME=ontobricks-app`` on the
     ``ontobricks-dev`` app's runtime env from the Apps UI; the
     explicit-override step (1) skips both SDK lookups entirely.

## Lakebase backend now sources catalog/schema/volume from the registries row

Context: a deployment whose ``volume`` resource happens to bind a
*different* Volume than the one referenced by the Lakebase
``registries`` row would render every Build-page existence check
against the wrong location and silently report all-red badges, even
though the underlying Delta view and ``.lbug`` archive were perfectly
intact. Concretely, ``ontobricks-dev`` was bound to
``benoit_cayla.ontobricks_deployed.registry`` while the row in
Lakebase pointed at ``benoit_cayla.ontobricks.OntoBricksRegistry`` —
where the artifacts actually live. ``RegistryCfg.from_domain`` was
unconditionally sourcing catalog/schema/volume from the bound Volume
path, so ``effective_view_table`` resolved to
``benoit_cayla.ontobricks_deployed.triplestore_cust360auto_v4`` (no
such view) and ``uc_version_path`` to
``/Volumes/benoit_cayla/ontobricks_deployed/registry/domains/cust360auto/V4``
(no such directory), turning every status badge red.

Root cause: with the Lakebase backend, the **Postgres row is the
source of truth** for where binary artefacts live — the Volume
resource binding is just a connection capability. The two had been
allowed to drift, and ``from_domain`` was reading the wrong one.

Fix: when ``backend`` resolves to ``"lakebase"``,
``RegistryCfg.from_domain`` now reads the
``(catalog, schema, volume)`` triplet from the singleton
``registries`` row in Lakebase. The Volume binding is only consulted
as a fall-back when Lakebase is unreachable or the row hasn't been
created yet — preserving the existing behaviour for first-time
initialization and offline cases.

Changes:

- ``src/back/objects/registry/store/lakebase/store.py``
  - New module-level helper ``fetch_lakebase_registry_triplet(schema,
    database)`` that opens a pooled connection and returns the
    ``(catalog, schema, volume)`` of the singleton ``registries`` row
    or ``None`` on any error / missing row.
  - Process-wide cache keyed on ``(schema, database)``: positive
    results live for the lifetime of the process, negative results
    have a short 60s TTL so a transient cold-start failure doesn't
    pin the app to the Volume fallback indefinitely.
  - Companion ``reset_lakebase_triplet_cache()`` for tests and
    admin-side row edits.

- ``src/back/objects/registry/RegistryService.py``
  - ``RegistryCfg.from_domain`` now short-circuits via
    ``fetch_lakebase_registry_triplet`` when ``backend == "lakebase"``
    and the helper returns a triplet; otherwise falls through to the
    pre-existing Volume-binding / env-var chain. Fail-soft: any
    Lakebase issue (offline, auth, missing row) silently falls back
    so the app never 500s on this path.
  - Docstring resolution-order block updated to call out the new
    Lakebase short-circuit explicitly.

- ``tests/test_registry.py``
  - New ``TestRegistryCfgFromDomainLakebaseTriplet`` covering:
    * Lakebase row overrides Volume binding when reachable.
    * Falls back to Volume binding when Lakebase returns ``None``.
    * Volume backend never consults Lakebase (zero wasted I/O).
    * The ``lakebase_database`` admin override is propagated to the
      triplet probe so two databases on the same Lakebase instance
      can each have their own registry row.

- ``tests/test_registry_store.py``
  - New ``TestFetchLakebaseRegistryTriplet`` covering: row-triplet
    return, positive-result caching (only one SELECT for repeated
    calls), missing-row → ``None``, pool-failure → ``None``,
    auth-failure → ``None``, distinct cache entries per
    ``(schema, database)`` pair.

Test plan:

- ``uv run pytest -q`` — full suite green (1875 passed).
- Manual: on a deployment where the Volume binding diverges from the
  Lakebase row, ``effective_view_table`` and ``uc_version_path`` now
  resolve to the row's catalog/schema/volume — Build-page badges flip
  back to green without any change to the Volume resource.

Operator notes:

- The triplet cache is process-local. After editing a ``registries``
  row directly in Postgres (e.g. to relocate the binary archive),
  restart the app or wait the negative TTL window — there's no
  hot-reload endpoint.
- This change is fully backwards-compatible with the legacy adoption
  path in ``_fetch_registry_id``: pre-existing schemas that adopt a
  legacy row continue to work, and the adopted row's
  ``(catalog, schema, volume)`` becomes the canonical answer for the
  rest of the process lifetime.

## domain.delta now follows RegistryCfg precedence (fixes red Triple-Store badge)

Context: even after the previous "Lakebase backend now sources
catalog/schema/volume from the registries row" change, the Build page
Triple-Store badge (``Unity Catalog VIEW``) was still rendering red on
``ontobricks-dev``. ``uc_version_path`` and ``uc_domain_path`` had been
correctly migrated to delegate to ``RegistryCfg.from_domain``, so they
picked up the Lakebase-row triplet — but ``DomainSession.delta`` was
still reading ``catalog`` and ``schema`` *directly* from
``self._data["settings"]["registry"]``. With the Lakebase backend
active, that dict can hold stale values (carry-over from a prior
session under a different binding), so ``effective_view_table`` would
resolve against the wrong catalog and the SQL existence check would
correctly report ``False`` — even though the view was alive and well
in the catalog.schema referenced by the Lakebase row.

Symptom on ``ontobricks-dev`` / ``cust360auto``:

- ``effective_view_table`` resolved to
  ``benoit_cayla.<stale>.triplestore_cust360auto_V4`` instead of
  ``benoit_cayla.ontobricks.triplestore_cust360auto_V4``.
- SQL ``DESCRIBE`` against the wrong catalog returned no row.
- Triple-Store badge rendered "Not found" while the view was visible
  via ``benoit_cayla.ontobricks_deployed.triplestore_cust360auto_V4``
  (Volume binding) and ``benoit_cayla.ontobricks.triplestore_…``
  (Lakebase row) — i.e. the user could *see* the view exists but the
  app couldn't.

Separately, the Registry-archive sub-badge was rendering "Not
archived". ``uc_version_path`` did resolve correctly to
``/Volumes/benoit_cayla/ontobricks/OntoBricksRegistry/domains/cust360auto/V4``,
but the dev app's service principal had **no privileges** on the
``OntoBricksRegistry`` Volume — only on the ``ontobricks_deployed.registry``
Volume that its resource binding pointed at. ``list_directory``
therefore returned an empty result and the check correctly inferred
the archive was missing.

Changes:

- ``src/back/objects/session/DomainSession.py``
  - ``DomainSession.delta`` now resolves ``catalog`` and ``schema``
    via ``RegistryCfg.from_domain(self, get_settings())`` so the same
    precedence applies as for ``uc_domain_path`` /
    ``uc_version_path``: UI override → Lakebase ``registries`` row →
    bound Volume resource path → env vars → raw session.
  - Wrapped in a ``try/except`` that falls back to the raw
    ``settings["registry"]`` values when the resolver raises (e.g.
    minimal test harnesses where ``shared.config.settings`` isn't
    importable). Same fail-soft contract as before — the property
    must never 500 the Build page.

- ``tests/test_domain_session.py``
  - New ``TestDomainSessionDelta`` class covering:
    * Volume-binding override beats stale ``settings.registry`` values.
    * Lakebase-row triplet wins on the Lakebase backend
      (``ontobricks`` schema, not the ``ontobricks_deployed`` binding).
    * Resolver failure falls back to raw session values without
      raising — keeps the Build page renderable in degraded modes.

Operator action (one-shot, not in code):

- Granted the dev app service principal
  ``7f3b3cad-b944-4f2c-ae04-a0f51384ca86`` the privileges it needed on
  the *real* artefact location:
  * ``USE_CATALOG`` on ``benoit_cayla``
  * ``USE_SCHEMA`` + ``SELECT`` on ``benoit_cayla.ontobricks``
  * ``READ_VOLUME`` on ``benoit_cayla.ontobricks.OntoBricksRegistry``
  Without these, even the corrected ``effective_view_table`` /
  ``uc_version_path`` would have hit access-denied and reported red.

Test plan:

- ``uv run pytest -q`` — full suite green (1878 passed).
- Manual: re-open the ``cust360auto`` project on ``ontobricks-dev``;
  the Triple-Store and Registry-archive badges flip back to green
  without any Volume re-binding.

## Registry Initialize: re-pin to current Volume binding + surface volume-creation result

Context: the OntoBricks dev sandbox was re-bound from ``benoit_cayla.
ontobricks_deployed.registry`` to ``benoit_cayla.ontobricks_deployed_test.
registry_test`` via the Apps ``volume`` resource (``databricks.yml``
``registry_schema=ontobricks_deployed_test``,
``registry_volume=registry_test``). After the rebind, the Registry
Configuration panel kept showing the *old* triplet — and re-clicking
``+ Initialize`` did not propagate the new triplet into the Lakebase
``registries`` row, so artefact paths and the panel's display stayed
stale forever.

Two compounding root causes:

1. ``RegistryCfg.from_domain`` for ``backend == "lakebase"`` reads
   ``catalog/schema/volume`` from the Lakebase ``registries`` row —
   that row is the source of truth for read paths so binary archive
   locations track where artefacts were *actually* built. But the
   Initialize handler was *also* using that row-derived cfg as its
   source of truth, so when ``_ensure_registry_row`` tried to UPSERT
   the new triplet, it actually re-upserted the stale one. Re-init
   was effectively a no-op on the row.
2. ``RegistryService.initialize`` swallowed the result of
   ``client.create_volume`` as a ``logger.warning`` only — admins
   couldn't tell whether the binary Volume creation step had run, let
   alone whether the SP had ``CREATE VOLUME`` on the schema. The
   Volume initialisation half of "Initialize" was effectively
   invisible from the UI.

Changes:

1. ``src/back/objects/registry/RegistryService.py`` — added
   ``prefer_volume_binding: bool = False`` kwarg to
   ``RegistryCfg.from_domain`` (and ``RegistryService.from_context``).
   When ``True`` the Lakebase row read is skipped and the cfg falls
   through to ``settings.registry_volume_path`` (the Apps volume
   binding). Used exclusively by the Initialize path so a re-bind +
   re-init cycle propagates the new triplet into the row. Default
   (``False``) preserves the row-as-source-of-truth contract for all
   other reads.
2. ``src/back/objects/registry/RegistryService.py`` —
   ``RegistryService.initialize`` (Lakebase branch) now surfaces the
   binary-Volume outcome in the returned message: "Created binary
   volume X.Y.Z." / "Binary volume X.Y.Z already exists." / "WARNING:
   could not create binary volume X.Y.Z — check ... CREATE VOLUME
   privilege ...". The schema/row creation still runs even when the
   Volume probe explodes (transient UC outages shouldn't block
   Lakebase schema initialisation).
3. ``src/back/objects/domain/SettingsService.py`` —
   ``initialize_registry_result`` now passes
   ``prefer_volume_binding=True`` to ``RegistryService.from_context``
   *and* invalidates the process-wide ``_TRIPLET_CACHE`` via
   ``reset_lakebase_triplet_cache()`` after a successful init, so the
   first read after Initialize sees the freshly-upserted row instead
   of the cached pre-init triplet.
4. ``databricks.yml`` — synced the ``registry_volume`` default to
   ``"registry_test"`` (the Volume name actually bound on the
   ``dev-lakebase`` target). Without this, ``databricks bundle
   deploy -t dev-lakebase`` failed with ``Volume
   'benoit_cayla.ontobricks_deployed_test.registry' does not exist``
   because the default and the live binding had drifted.
5. ``tests/test_registry.py`` — added five regression tests:
   - ``TestRegistryCfgFromDomainLakebaseTriplet
     .test_prefer_volume_binding_skips_lakebase_row`` — pins that the
     Initialize-path flag bypasses ``fetch_lakebase_registry_triplet``
     and falls through to the Volume binding.
   - ``TestInitializeLakebase`` (4 tests) covering: volume-creation
     happy path with row upsert, "already exists" message, ``CREATE
     VOLUME`` privilege failure surfaced as a warning (schema still
     initialised), and ``list_volumes`` exception handled (schema
     still initialised, error included in the message).

Files modified:

- ``src/back/objects/registry/RegistryService.py``
- ``src/back/objects/domain/SettingsService.py``
- ``databricks.yml``
- ``tests/test_registry.py``

Test plan:

- ``uv run pytest tests/test_registry.py -q`` — 91 passed (5 new).
- ``uv run pytest -q`` — full suite green (1892 passed).
- Manual: ``databricks bundle deploy -t dev-lakebase`` succeeded;
  ``databricks bundle run ontobricks_dev_app -t dev-lakebase`` brought
  the app up clean. After clicking ``+ Initialize`` on the Registry
  page, the ``registries`` row UPSERT now propagates the new
  ``(benoit_cayla, ontobricks_deployed_test, registry_test)`` triplet,
  the response message includes the Volume status, and a page reload
  shows the corrected configuration.

## Auto-Map: don't append `LIMIT` to non-SELECT statements in `execute_sql` tool

Context: during an auto-map run the agent submitted a metadata
statement (``DESCRIBE benoit_cayla.customer.payment``) to the
``execute_sql`` tool. The tool unconditionally rewrote it as
``DESCRIBE benoit_cayla.customer.payment LIMIT 3`` and the SQL
warehouse rejected it with::

    [PARSE_SYNTAX_ERROR] Syntax error at or near '3': extra input '3'.
    SQLSTATE: 42601 (line 1, pos 45)
    == SQL ==
    DESCRIBE benoit_cayla.customer.payment LIMIT 3

Spark SQL only accepts ``LIMIT`` after ``SELECT`` / set-operation
queries — ``DESCRIBE``, ``SHOW``, ``EXPLAIN`` reject it.

Fix: ``tool_execute_sql`` now strips & re-appends ``LIMIT _SAMPLE_ROWS``
only when the statement starts with ``SELECT`` or ``WITH`` (case-
insensitive, after stripping a trailing semicolon). Anything else runs
verbatim, so the agent can use ``DESCRIBE`` / ``SHOW`` to introspect
schema without provoking a parse error and self-correct properly when
its row-returning queries are wrong.

Changes
1. ``src/agents/tools/sql.py`` — gate ``LIMIT`` rewrite on a
   ``^(SELECT|WITH)\b`` match against the trimmed SQL; non-row
   statements are executed as-is.

Modified files
- ``src/agents/tools/sql.py``

Test result: ``pytest`` — 1892 passed in 62.30s.

## Auto-Map agent: forbid DESCRIBE/SHOW/EXPLAIN via execute_sql in SYSTEM_PROMPT

Context: companion to the previous ``execute_sql`` LIMIT-rewrite fix.
Even though the tool now tolerates non-``SELECT`` statements, the
intended contract is that ``execute_sql`` only runs row-returning
queries, and that ``get_metadata`` is the single path for schema
introspection. The earlier crash showed the model occasionally
deviates (temperature=0.1 still leaves room for variance), so we make
the contract explicit in the prompt to cut down on wasted iterations
spent re-introspecting tables the agent already has in context.

Changes
1. ``src/agents/agent_auto_assignment/engine.py`` — add a GENERAL RULES
   bullet stating: only pass row-returning queries (``SELECT`` /
   ``WITH``) to ``execute_sql``; use ``get_metadata`` for schema
   introspection; never use ``DESCRIBE`` / ``SHOW`` / ``EXPLAIN`` via
   the SQL tool.

Modified files
- ``src/agents/agent_auto_assignment/engine.py``

Test result: ``pytest`` — 1892 passed in 59.71s.

## Lakebase init probe: surface live (database, role, schema_exists) in the no_usage error

Context: deployed app reports "Schema ontobricks_registry visible but
the app service principal lacks USAGE. Run scripts/bootstrap-lakebase-perms.sh
(or grant manually) and refresh." even when the operator confirms the
GRANTs are in place. Two common causes the old message could not
distinguish:

  * grants applied to a different Lakebase database than the one the
    Apps ``postgres`` resource binds (each Lakebase project may host
    several databases, and Postgres permissions are per-database, so
    USAGE on schema ``X`` in database ``A`` is invisible from a
    session connected to database ``B``);
  * the schema name resolved from settings differs from the one the
    operator granted on (e.g. legacy ``ontobricks_registry`` vs a
    Settings-overridden ``lakebase_schema``).

Both look identical to the old probe — ``has_schema_privilege`` simply
returned ``f`` and the message named only the schema, leaving the
operator with no way to tell whether the GRANT was wrong or the binding
was wrong.

Fix: the probe now selects ``current_database()``, ``current_user`` and
``EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM pg_namespace WHERE nspname = <schema>)``
alongside the privilege check. The error message names all three so the
operator can immediately see ``(database, role, schema_exists)`` and
spot the mismatch::

    Role 'sp-<uuid>' lacks USAGE on schema 'ontobricks_registry'
    in database 'databricks_postgres'. Run
    scripts/bootstrap-lakebase-perms.sh -i <instance>
    -d databricks_postgres -s ontobricks_registry -a <app-name>, ...

If the schema is absent in the bound database the probe now returns a
distinct message that names the live ``current_database`` and points
the operator at the bundle's ``lakebase_database_resource``.

Changes
1. ``src/back/objects/registry/store/lakebase/store.py`` — replace the
   single ``has_schema_privilege`` query with a 4-column probe
   (``current_database()``, ``current_user``, privilege bit, schema
   existence). Compose two distinct ``no_usage`` messages depending on
   whether the schema exists in the connected database.
2. ``tests/test_registry_store.py`` — update the two existing
   ``no_usage``/``no_registries_table``/``no_registry_row``/``ok``
   tests to feed the new 4-tuple shape; add
   ``test_no_usage_when_schema_missing_in_bound_database`` covering
   the new schema-missing branch and asserting the live database name
   appears in the error.

Modified files
