## bootstrap-lakebase-perms.sh: align defaults with the dev sandbox bundle

Context: the script defaulted to ``-i ontobricks-app -d ontobricks_registry``,
which made sense for the production layout but is wrong for the
current dev sandbox. ``databricks.yml`` binds the Apps ``postgres``
resource to the Autoscaling project ``ontobricks-test`` and the
``databricks_postgres`` Lakebase database (the registry schema lives
inside that database — see the ``lakebase_database_resource``
variable comment). Running the script with defaults therefore landed
``GRANT USAGE`` on a database the runtime never connects to, leaving
``has_schema_privilege(current_user, 'ontobricks_registry', 'USAGE')``
false in the actually-bound ``databricks_postgres`` and surfacing the
``no_usage`` panel error.

Fix: change the defaults to match the dev sandbox layout. Operators
running for the production app keep using ``-i ontobricks-app
-d ontobricks_registry -a ontobricks`` explicitly. The new
``Defaults match the dev sandbox`` header documents the rationale
and the override flags inline.

Changes
1. ``scripts/bootstrap-lakebase-perms.sh`` — flip defaults to
   ``INSTANCE=ontobricks-test``, ``DATABASE=databricks_postgres``,
   ``APPS=("ontobricks-dev")`` (the latter was already the default).
   Updated the usage block accordingly.

Modified files
- ``scripts/bootstrap-lakebase-perms.sh``

Test result: ``pytest`` — 1892 passed (script change has no Python coverage).

## bootstrap-lakebase-perms.sh: switch to Postgres API for endpoint + JWT

Context: even after aligning the script's defaults to the dev sandbox
(``-i ontobricks-test -d databricks_postgres``), the script still
crashed on first run with::

    json.decoder.JSONDecodeError: Expecting value: line 1 column 1 (char 0)

Root cause: the script resolved the instance host via
``GET /api/2.0/database/instances/<name>``, which is part of the
**legacy Database Instance API** that does not see Autoscaling-only
projects. That endpoint returned a 404 with an empty body, ``python3
json.load(sys.stdin)`` blew up, and PGHOST stayed empty. Same story
for the JWT mint via ``/api/2.0/database/credentials``.

Fix: replace both legacy API calls with the Postgres Autoscaling API
that the runtime ``LakebaseAuth`` already uses.

- Endpoint resolution: walk
  ``GET /api/2.0/postgres/projects/<project>/branches`` → for each
  branch ``GET /api/2.0/postgres/<branch_path>/endpoints`` → pick the
  first endpoint whose ``status.hosts.host`` is populated. Print the
  host (becomes PGHOST) and the full endpoint resource path.
- JWT mint: ``POST /api/2.0/postgres/credentials`` with
  ``{"endpoint": "<endpoint_resource>"}`` instead of
  ``/api/2.0/database/credentials`` with ``instance_names`` — the
  legacy mint cannot scope to Autoscaling-only project endpoints.

Verified end-to-end against the dev sandbox::

    Project  : ontobricks-test (ep-damp-art-d1l8gclo.database.us-west-2…)
    Endpoint : projects/ontobricks-test/branches/production/endpoints/primary
    Database : databricks_postgres
    Schema   : ontobricks_registry
    Acting as: benoit.cayla@databricks.com
    Apps     : ontobricks-dev
      [ontobricks-dev] service principal: 7f3b3cad-b944-4f2c-ae04-a0f51384ca86
      [ontobricks-dev] ✓ granted USAGE + DML on schema 'ontobricks_registry'

Changes
1. ``scripts/bootstrap-lakebase-perms.sh`` — replace the
   ``/api/2.0/database/instances/<name>`` host lookup with an inline
   ``python3`` heredoc that walks the Postgres API; replace the
   ``/api/2.0/database/credentials`` JWT mint with a
   ``/api/2.0/postgres/credentials`` POST scoped to the resolved
   endpoint resource. Output now also names the endpoint path so
   operators can verify it matches what ``databricks.yml`` binds.

Modified files
- ``scripts/bootstrap-lakebase-perms.sh``

Test result: not covered by ``pytest`` (shell script); validated by
running it end-to-end against the dev sandbox and observing the
expected GRANT verification (``USAGE=t``, ``SELECT registries=t``).

----------------------------------------------------------------------
Fix: Mapping page "Reset" button no longer fires
----------------------------------------------------------------------

Context
~~~~~~~

On the Mapping page, the top-right red ``Reset`` button (``id=resetMappingsBtn``
in ``_mapping_information.html``) silently did nothing. Regression
introduced in commit ``5f2ee0e`` (2026-04-16): the inline
``onclick="confirmResetMappings()"`` was removed from the partial and
replaced with a top-level ``addEventListener`` call at the bottom of
``mapping-information.js``. Because ``mapping.html`` loads the script
**before** the partial is rendered into the DOM (script tag at line 21,
partial included at line 51), the listener wiring ran while
``getElementById('resetMappingsBtn')`` was still ``null``, so no click
handler was ever attached.

Changes
~~~~~~~

1. ``src/front/static/global/js/mapping-information.js`` — moved the
   button wiring into ``_initMappingInformationButtons()`` and gated
   it on ``DOMContentLoaded`` (with an immediate run if the script is
   loaded after parsing finishes). Idempotent via a
   ``data-ob-reset-wired`` flag so re-init is safe. Same wrapper
   re-runs ``setupImportExportButtons()`` for consistency.

Modified files
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

- ``src/front/static/global/js/mapping-information.js``

Test result: not covered by ``pytest`` (front-end only). Verified
manually — the Reset button now opens the confirmation dialog and
clears all entity / relationship mappings.

----------------------------------------------------------------------
Fix: align deploy tooling with the dev-sandbox-only bundle
----------------------------------------------------------------------

Context
~~~~~~~

After ``databricks.yml`` was carved on 2026-04-27 to manage only the
``ontobricks-dev`` sandbox app, ``scripts/deploy.sh``,
``scripts/bootstrap-app-permissions.sh`` and the ``Makefile`` were
left referring to the no-longer-bundled production apps
(``ontobricks_app``, ``mcp_ontobricks_app``, ``mcp-ontobricks``).
The visible failure modes were:

- ``make deploy-all`` deployed cleanly but then failed on
  ``Error: resource with key "ontobricks_app" not found`` when it
  tried to start the (non-existent) production app.
- A plain ``make deploy`` runs target ``dev``, which does **not**
  declare the ``postgres`` resource. DAB reconciles the live app to
  match the spec, so each deploy silently stripped the Lakebase
  binding from ``ontobricks-dev`` and the registry fell back to
  Volume-only mode.

Changes
~~~~~~~

1. ``scripts/deploy.sh`` — rewritten to target a single resource key
   (``ontobricks_dev_app``) and a single app name
   (``ontobricks-dev``). Default target is now ``dev-lakebase`` so
   the Lakebase Postgres binding survives every deploy. Removed the
   dead ``--all``, ``--mcp-only``, cross-app permission grants and
   the production apps verification loop. Bind path now binds only
   ``ontobricks_dev_app → ontobricks-dev``.

2. ``Makefile`` — replaced the stale deploy targets with three:

   - ``make deploy``         → ``-t dev-lakebase`` (default; Lakebase backend)
   - ``make deploy-volume``  → ``-t dev`` (Volume-only fallback)
   - ``make deploy-no-run``  → ``-t dev-lakebase --no-run``

   ``bundle-validate`` and ``bundle-summary`` now run against
   ``-t dev-lakebase`` so the resolved spec includes the postgres
   resource. ``bootstrap-perms`` now invokes the script with
   ``ontobricks-dev`` explicitly. Dropped ``deploy-all``,
   ``deploy-mcp``, ``deploy-prod`` from ``.PHONY`` and ``help``.

3. ``scripts/bootstrap-app-permissions.sh`` — default app list
   shrunk from ``("ontobricks" "mcp-ontobricks")`` to
   ``("ontobricks-dev")``; usage block updated. Multi-app
   pass-through behavior is unchanged.

Modified files
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

- ``scripts/deploy.sh``
- ``scripts/bootstrap-app-permissions.sh``
- ``Makefile``

Test result: shell scripts pass ``bash -n``;
``databricks bundle validate -t dev`` and
``databricks bundle validate -t dev-lakebase`` both succeed (only
the pre-existing cosmetic warnings about the empty ``htmlcov`` /
``mlruns`` / ``mlartifacts`` exclude patterns). Full ``pytest`` run
still green at 1892 passed (no Python code touched).

----------------------------------------------------------------------
Fix: auto-bootstrap Lakebase schema GRANTs on every dev-lakebase deploy
----------------------------------------------------------------------

Context
~~~~~~~

Whenever the postgres resource binding is unbound and rebound — which
happens any time the deploy target switches between ``dev`` and
``dev-lakebase`` — Lakebase loses the schema-level GRANTs the app's
service principal needs. The runtime then fails with::

    Role '7f3b3cad-b944-4f2c-ae04-a0f51384ca86' lacks USAGE on schema
    'ontobricks_registry' in database 'databricks_postgres'.

The remediation script ``scripts/bootstrap-lakebase-perms.sh`` already
existed and was idempotent, but nothing called it after a deploy, so
operators had to re-run it by hand every single time.

Changes
~~~~~~~

1. ``scripts/deploy.sh`` — new step 8 invokes
   ``scripts/bootstrap-lakebase-perms.sh -a ontobricks-dev`` whenever
   ``$TARGET == "dev-lakebase"``. Failures are tolerated (e.g. first
   deploy before ``Settings > Registry > Initialize`` has created the
   schema, or ``psql`` not on PATH) and surface a one-line follow-up
   command.

2. ``Makefile`` — new ``make bootstrap-lakebase`` target that wraps
   the same script for the dev sandbox, so the GRANT can be re-run
   on its own without redeploying. ``.PHONY`` and ``help`` updated.

Modified files
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

- ``scripts/deploy.sh``
- ``Makefile``

Test result: ``bash -n scripts/deploy.sh`` syntax-clean; live run of
``make bootstrap-lakebase`` against the dev sandbox printed::

    [ontobricks-dev] ✓ granted USAGE + DML on schema 'ontobricks_registry'
    === Done — Lakebase schema bootstrap complete ===

restoring the runtime path. ``pytest`` not re-run (no Python code
touched).
